  "id": "sec-piecewise-functions",
  "level": "1",
  "url": "sec-piecewise-functions.html",
  "type": "Section",
  "number": "1.2",
  "title": "Piecewise Functions (ALEKS 1.7)",
  "body": " Piecewise Functions (ALEKS 1.7)   Graph piecewise-defined functions  A piecewise function is a function built from pieces of different functions over different intervals.   The absolute value function can be written as a piecewise function.    Graph of Absolute Value Function     f_pos(x) = x  f_neg(x) = -x             Graph the function.      Graph of piecewise function     f1(x) = -4  f2(x) = -x  f3(x) = sqrt(x-1)                   REMARK: When a function has no \"gaps\" it is said to be continuous . Informally, this means we can draw the function without lifting our pencil from the page. The formal definition of a continuous function will be studied in calculus.    Suppose that the function is defined for all real numbers as follows.   Graph the function . Then determine whether or not the function is continuous.     Graph of piecewise function     f1(x) = 6  f2(x) = x^2 - 10  f3(x) = 2*x - 2                   Choosing a graph to fit a narrative  Piecewise functions aptly model distance-time graphs.     Choose the graph that best represents each scenario below.     (A) Kaitlin goes from her house to the store.    Graph A     f(x) = x           Graph B     f(x) = -0.4*x + 3           Graph C     f(x) = 3           Graph D                   (B) Jim leaves his house on his bike. He rides at a constant speed until he reaches a lemonade stand, where he parks his bike and takes a rest. Then he turns around and bikes home as fast as he can.    Graph A     f1(x) = x  f2(x) = 2  f3(x) = x-1.3             Graph B     f1(x) = x  f2(x) = 2  f3(x) = -x+5.3             Graph C     f1(x) = 2*x  f2(x) = 2  f3(x) = (x-1.8)^3 + 2             Graph D     f1(x) = 2  f2(x) = 5*x-2  f3(x) = -0.5*x+4                Students - Check your understanding    Graph the function.    Blank Grid                Choose the graph that best represents the following statement. A car slows down as it approaches a stop sign.    Graph A     f(x) = x           Graph B     f(x) = -0.4*x + 3           Graph C     f(x) = 3           Graph D                "
