  "title": "Division of Polynomials (ALEKS 2.3)",
  "body": " Division of Polynomials (ALEKS 2.3)  We will examine two types of polynomial division: long division and synthetic division. Polynomial division can be used to factor a polynomial equation and find the zeros of a polynomial.   The Division Algorithm   Suppose that and are polynomials where and the degree of is less than or equal to the degree of . Then there exists unique polynomials and such that    where either the degree of is less than , or is the zero polynomial.     Divide polynomials using long division  The polynomial is the dividend , is the divisor , is the quotient , and is the remainder .   To begin the division always write the terms of the dividend and divisor in descending order with zeros as place holders for missing powers of .    Use polynomial long division to divide .   4in     Use polynomial long division to divide .   3.2in    Divide polynomials using synthetic division  We can use synthetic division when the divisor is a binomial of the form and is a constant.        The setup:   Step 1: Write the value of in a box.  Step 2: Write the coefficients of the dividend to the right of the box.  Step 3: Skip a line and draw a horizontal line below the list of coefficients.  Step 4: Bring down the leading coefficient in dividend and write it below line.   The division:   Step 5: Multiply the value of by the number below the line. Write the result in the next column above the line.  Step 6: Add the numbers in the column above the line, and write result below line.   Repeat steps 5 and 6 until all columns have been completed.  The right-most number below the line is the remainder. The numbers below the line are coefficients of the quotient in order by the degree of the term.  Students - Check your understanding    Divide using polynomial long division.    4in     Divide using synthetic division.     2.2in     2.2in     Apply the Remainder and Factor Theorems  The value of equals the remainder we get from dividing by . On the other hand, the factor theorem tells us when is a factor of .    Remainder Theorem   If a polynomial is divided by , then the remainder is .      Given , use the remainder theorem to evaluate .   1.5in    Factor Theorem   Let be a polynomial. If , then is a factor of . If is a factor of , then .      Use the factor theorem to determine if is a factor of .    1.5in    REMARK: Polynomials may also be evaluated over the set of complex numbers rather than restricting to the set of real numbers. A complex number is a zero of a polynomial  if  .    Use both the factor theorem and the remainder theorem to determine if is a zero of    3in     Factor , given that is a factor.   4in     Write a polynomial of degree in standard form that has the zeros , with a multiplicity of two, and .   2.5in   Students - Check your understanding    For which of the following functions is the given value of a zero? Select all that apply.    ;  0.5in    ;  0.5in    ;  0.5in      Find such that has the factor .   0.25in  0.25in  0.25in  0.25in     Choose the function that has as a factor.        "
