  "body": " Zeros of Polynomials (ALEKS 2.4)   Zeros of a Polynomial   The zeros of a polynomial  are the solutions to the equation .  The real zeros of are the -intercepts on the graph of the function.     Rational Zero Theorem   If has integer coefficients and , and if (written in lowest terms) is a rational zero of , then is a factor of the constant term and is a factor of the leading coefficient .  If a rational zero exists for a polynomial, then it must be of the form      Apply the Rational Zero Theorem  The Rational Zero Theorem limits the possible number of rational zeros to a finite number of tasks but does not guarantee the existence of rational zeros.     For    List all possible rational zeros.  1.5in    Find the real zeros and their multiplicities.  1.5in     Fundamental Theorem of Algebra   If is a polynomial of degree with complex coefficients, then has at least one complex zero.     Linear Factorization Theorem   If where and , then where are complex numbers.     Apply the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra guarantees that a zero exists. Every polynomial of degree has at most real zeros. To factor over the real numbers:   Step 1: Use the Rational Zeros Theorem to identify the possible rational zeros.  Step 2: Use the Factor Theorem or Remainder Theorem to test possible zeros.  Step 3: Each time a zero is found, use factoring techniques or polynomial division to find the remaining factors.      Given that is one solution to , find the remaining solutions.   3in    Important Note: Not all polynomials have rational solutions. For example    Conjugate Zeros Theorem   If is a polynomial with real coefficients and if ( ) is a zero of then its conjugate is also a zero of .    0.9in    Suppose that is a polynomial of degree whose coefficients are real numbers. Answer the following questions given that has the following zeros: , ,     Find another zero of .  1.5in    What is the maximum number of real zeros that can have?  1.5in    What is the maximum number of nonreal zeros that can have?  1.5in     Number of Zeros of a Polynomial   If is a polynomial of degree with complex coefficients, then has exactly complex zeros provided that each zero is counted by its multiplicity.      The function below has at least one rational zero. Use this fact to find all zeros of the function and express as a product of linear factors.    4in     Find a polynomial of degree with real coefficients and the following zeros:    5.5in     Find a polynomial with real coefficients of degree with zeros and that satisfies the condition .   3in   Students - Check your understanding    Which of the following contains all possible rational zeros for ?      0.25in     0.25in     0.25in     0.25in    0.75in    Which of the following is not a possible zero of the following function? Select all that apply.         0.75in    Decide whether the following statement is true or false.  A polynomial function of degree with real coefficients could have , , , and as its zeros. Choose the correct answer below.    False  0.2in    True  0.2in    Students - Check your understanding    The function below has at least one rational zero. Use this fact to find all the zeros of the function.    2.8in     One zero of is . Find the remaining zeros of the function.   2.8in     Find a degree polynomial with zeros of , with multiplicity , and .   2.8in   "
